Our findings admit an interpretive analogy with Popper's falsifiability criterion (1959): a false theory that requires ad hoc corrections to accommodate observations has higher description length than a true one. The analogy is limited -- the model does not "test" theories -- but the structural parallel is suggestive.", "new_string": "The 1B experiment on real web text (Section 4.7) provides initial evidence that the effect persists beyond toy scale and synthetic data, but all our experiments remain far below the scale of production LLMs. Whether these findings extend to large-scale pretraining on heterogeneous real-world corpora remains an open question. We view our results as identifying a mechanism and its boundary conditions, not as direct claims about production LLMs.

The pattern admits an analogy with Popper's falsifiability criterion (1959): a false theory requiring ad hoc corrections to fit observations has higher description length than a parsimonious true one. The analogy is limited -- the model does not test theories against evidence -- but the structural parallel between MDL-driven preference and falsifiability-driven theory selection is suggestive."}
